Deep Learning Project: Street View Housing Number Digit Recognition¶

Marks: 60¶

Context¶

One of the most interesting tasks in deep learning is to recognize objects in natural scenes. The ability to process visual information using machine learning algorithms can be very useful as demonstrated in various applications.

The SVHN dataset contains over 600,000 labeled digits cropped from street-level photos. It is one of the most popular image recognition datasets. It has been used in neural networks created by Google to improve the map quality by automatically transcribing the address numbers from a patch of pixels. The transcribed number with a known street address helps pinpoint the location of the building it represents.

Objective¶

Our objective is to predict the number depicted inside the image by using Artificial or Fully Connected Feed Forward Neural Networks and Convolutional Neural Networks. We will go through various models of each and finally select the one that is giving us the best performance.

Dataset¶

Here, we will use a subset of the original data to save some computation time. The dataset is provided as a .h5 file. The basic preprocessing steps have been applied on the dataset.

# Define the model
def nn_model_1():
    model = Sequential()

    # Add layers as per the architecture mentioned above in the same sequence
    model.add(Dense(64, activation='relu', input_shape=(1024,)))
    model.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(10, activation='softmax'))  # Assuming 10 classes

    # Compile the model
    model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001),
                  metrics=['accuracy'])

    return model

# Build the model

# Fit the model

Observations:

  • looking at the overall upward trend in the data, it is evident that the model is learning well because both the training and validation accuracy are improving
  • The training accuracy (blue dashed line) starts at a level below 0.2 and increases steadily as the number of epochs grows. It appears to start to plateau around epoch 17, suggesting that the model is starting to converge and is achieving as much learning from the training data as possible given its architecture and hyperparameters.
  • The validation accuracy (red dashed line) follows a similar upward trend as the training accuracy. This indicates that the model is generalizing well to unseen data.
  • for the beginning epochs, it seems that the model is slightly overfitting the data as the validation accuracy is above the training accuracy.
  • the gap between the training and validation accuracy is fairly narrow and converges around 12 ephochs. this is a good sign because it shows that the model is no longer overfitting on the training set at larger epochs and maintains an ability to generalize
  • Both accuracies are beginning to plateau by the end of the graphed epochs, especially the training accuracy. This plateauing can mean that further training beyond 20 epochs might not yield significant improvements without changes to the model or learning process (such as tuning hyperparameters, using regularization techniques, or collecting more data).
  • While the model is learning, the final accuracy is around 0.6781. There may be room to improve the model further to achieve higher accuracy. Techniques such as adding more layers, nodes, or using different regularization methods like dropout or early stopping could be explored.

In [109]:
def nn_model_2(input_shape, num_classes):
    model = Sequential()

    # First hidden layer
    model.add(Dense(256, activation='relu', input_shape=input_shape))

    # Second hidden layer
    model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))

    # Dropout layer
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    # Third hidden layer
    model.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))

    # Fourth hidden layer
    model.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))

    # Fifth hidden layer
    model.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))

    # BatchNormalization layer
    model.add(BatchNormalization())

    # Output layer
    model.add(Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax'))

    # Compile the model
    model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.0005),
                  metrics=['accuracy'])

    return model

# Assuming the input shape and the number of classes have been defined
input_shape = (1024,)
num_classes = 10

# Create the model
model_2 = nn_model_2(input_shape, num_classes)

# Print the model summary
model_2.summary()

# Fit the model
history_model_2 = model_2.fit(X_train_normalized, y_train_encoded, validation_split=0.2, batch_size=128, verbose=1, epochs=30)

Model Architecture¶

  • Write a function that returns a sequential model with the following architecture:
    • First Convolutional layer with 16 filters and the kernel size of 3x3. Use the 'same' padding and provide the input shape = (32, 32, 1)
    • Add a LeakyRelu layer with the slope equal to 0.1
    • Second Convolutional layer with 32 filters and the kernel size of 3x3 with 'same' padding
    • Another LeakyRelu with the slope equal to 0.1
    • A max-pooling layer with a pool size of 2x2
    • Flatten the output from the previous layer
    • Add a dense layer with 32 nodes
    • Add a LeakyRelu layer with the slope equal to 0.1
    • Add the final output layer with nodes equal to the number of classes, i.e., 10 and 'softmax' as the activation function
    • Compile the model with the loss equal to categorical_crossentropy, optimizer equal to Adam(learning_rate = 0.001), and metric equal to 'accuracy'. Do not fit the model here, just return the compiled model.
  • Call the function cnn_model_1 and store the output in a new variable.
  • Print the summary of the model.
  • Fit the model on the training data with a validation split of 0.2, batch size = 32, verbose = 1, and epochs = 20. Store the model building history to use later for visualization.

Build and train a CNN model as per the above mentioned architecture.¶

In [126]:
def cnn_model_1(input_shape, num_classes):
    #initializing the sequential model
    model = Sequential()

    # First Convolutional layer with 16 filters and a kernal size of 3x3
    model.add(Conv2D(16, kernel_size=(3, 3), padding='same', input_shape=input_shape)) #padding 'same' ensures the output image size is the same as the input image size
    # LeakyRelu layer with a slope of 0.1
    model.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))

    # Second Convolutional layer with 32 filters and a kernal size of 3x3
    model.add(Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(3, 3), padding='same'))
    # LeakyRelu layer with a slope of 0.1
    model.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))

    # Max-pooling layer with a pool size of 2x2
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

    # Flatten the output
    model.add(Flatten())

    # Dense layer with 32 nodes
    model.add(Dense(32))
    # LeakyRelu layer with a slope of 0.1
    model.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))

    # Output layer with nodes equal to the 'num_classes' and the softmax activation function
    model.add(Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax'))

    # Compile the model  with the loss equal to categorical_crossentropy, optimizer equal to Adam(learning_rate = 0.001), and metric equal to 'accuracy'.
    model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001),
                  metrics=['accuracy'])

    return model

# defining the function inputs
input_shape = (32, 32, 1)
num_classes = 10

# Create the model and save it in new object called cnn_model1

    • Third Convolutional layer with 32 filters and the kernel size of 3x3 with 'same' padding

    • Add a LeakyRelu layer with the slope equal to 0.1

    • Flatten the output from the previous layer
    • Add a dense layer with 32 nodes

Build and train the second CNN model as per the above mentioned architecture.¶

In [131]:
def cnn_model_2(input_shape, num_classes):
    # Initialize the Sequential model
    model = Sequential()

    # First Convolutional layer with 16 filters of size 3x3 and 'same' padding ensures output is the same size as the input
    model.add(Conv2D(16, kernel_size=(3, 3), padding='same', input_shape=input_shape))
    # Add LeakyReLU activation with slope of 0.1
    model.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))

    # Second Convolutional layer with 32 filters of size 3x3 and 'same' padding
    model.add(Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(3, 3), padding='same'))
    # Add LeakyReLU activation with slope of 0.1
    model.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))

    # MaxPooling layer to reduce spatial dimensions by taking the maximum value over 2x2 patches
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
    # BatchNormalization layer to normalize the activations of the previous layer at each batch
    model.add(BatchNormalization())

    # Third Convolutional layer with 32 filters of size 3x3 and 'same' padding
    model.add(Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(3, 3), padding='same'))
    # Add LeakyReLU activation with slope of 0.1
    model.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))

    # Fourth Convolutional layer with 64 filters of size 3x3 and 'same' padding
    model.add(Conv2D(64, kernel_size=(3, 3), padding='same'))
    # Add LeakyReLU activation with slope of 0.1
    model.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))

    # Another MaxPooling layer with a pool size of 2x2
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
    # Another BatchNormalization layer
    model.add(BatchNormalization())

    # Flatten the output of the previous layer to prepare it for the dense layers
    model.add(Flatten())

    # Dense layer with 32 nodes
    model.add(Dense(32))
    # Add LeakyReLU activation with slope of 0.1
    model.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))

    # Dropout layer to prevent overfitting by randomly setting a fraction rate of input units to 0 at each update during training time
    model.add(Dropout(0.5))

    # Output layer with a number of nodes corresponding to the number of classes and softmax activation
    model.add(Dense(num_classes, activation='softmax'))

    # Compile the model with the categorical crossentropy loss, the adam optimizer, and accuracy as a metric
    model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001),
                  metrics=['accuracy'])

    return model

# Defining the function inputs
input_shape = (32, 32, 1)
num_classes = 10

# Create the model using the defined function and save it in new object called 'cnn_model2'
cnn_model2 = cnn_model_2(input_shape, num_classes)

# Print the summary of the model to verify the architecture
print(cnn_model2.summary())

cnn_history_2 = cnn_model2.fit(X_train, y_train_encoded, validation_split=0.2, batch_size=128, verbose=1, epochs=30)

  • the training accuracy in this plot starts at around 0.55 and sharply increases to 90% after 10 epochs
    • It continues to gradually improve throughout the remaining epochs, leveling off close to 95%. -The validation accuracy initially increases in parallel with the training accuracy but starts to plateau sooner, at around the 10th epoch, at just above 90%.
  • The validation accuracy shows some fluctuations but generally maintains a stable value, indicating that the model's ability to generalize to new data is consistent after a certain point.
  • there seems to be some overfitting but the gap does not widen significantly, which indicates that the overfitting is not severe
  • the model performs very well on both the training and validation sets, which is something we aim for in a machine learning task
  • The slight fluctuations in validation accuracy could be a sign of the model's sensitivity to the specific data points in the validation set or the stochastic nature of the training process (e.g., due to mini-batch gradient descent).
  • the accuracy for both the validation and training set plateau after about 15 epochs
    • it might be benefitial to impliment early stopping when the validation accuracy starts to plateau even as the training set improves. this could reduce computational time and computation resources needed
  • techniques such as regularization or further hyperparameter tuning could possibly help bridge the gap between training and validation accuracy.

    • the model uses small filters to capture local patterns
    • LeakyReLU layers could help in avoiding dead neurons during training by allowing small gradient when the unit is inactive

    • this model shows a higher training accuracy compared to all the other models and maintains a high validation accuracy, which is a strong indicator of its performance.
